&gt; 
&gt; I haven&#39;t seen any explicit studies on population size in NEAT
&gt; specifically, but there have been such studies for genetic algorithms
&gt; in general.  I think Kenneth De Jong&#39;s textbook, &quot;Evolutionary
&gt; Computation: A Unified Perspective&quot; examines it.
&gt; 
&gt; However, of course as people have pointed out in NEAT it&#39;s not just a
&gt; question of a healthy population but of healthy species, since each
&gt; species is like its own little population.  In other words, the
&gt; species need enough internal diversity to drive their own
&gt; explorations.  My own rule of thumb has been a minimum of 15 members
&gt; per species (on average) to keep them healthy.  I&#39;m sure 30 is even
&gt; safer.  
&gt; 
&gt; Another thing to note is that the population size you need can vary
&gt; wildly by problem and it can be surprising.  For pole balancing, it
&gt; turns out that you can solve it fastest with a minuscule population of
&gt; size under 20 total (that&#39;s for the whole population!).   That is
&gt; because smaller populations are greedier (they concentrate resources
&gt; on a small part of the search space) and apparently pole balancing
&gt; benefits greatly from greedy search.  However, that is a specific
&gt; property of pole balancing and I would not expect it to carry over to
&gt; more significant domains.  Surely in some domains having a population
&gt; over 1000 would lead to the most interesting results, if only you can
&gt; afford the luxury of the added computational cost of a large population.
&gt; 
&gt; ken
